<A taste of Merely Musing, written the day the concept came to me>

>"...as the hulking form of the beast slowly, tantalizingly lowered onto his length, Anon knew one thing: he wasn't getting out of this with an unbroken pelvis."
>Done. Your story is finally, finally done. You've been working on it for nearly two weeks now, making sure it's absolutely perfect.
>The idea came to you in your dreams. A human Anon, cornered in his own home by a huge monster. At first, it was purely a thriller. Then... your inspirations took a more suggestive lean. The monster became female, her prey being pursued for purposes of passion, rather than hunger.
>It became a story worthy of sharing with /hmofa/. And so, you're ready to share your work with the world. You solve the Captcha, and mouse over the Post button...
>Before you can click, you are suddenly grabbed by two string hands; one grabs your arm, and one wraps around your mouth. You're pulled away from your desk, your chair rolling away from your work.
>Certain that you're being robbed, you screw your eyes shut. The intruder roughly spins your chair around, and takes their hand off your mouth.
>"M-my wallet's on the nightstand. Just take it, and don't kill me, please."
>You're met with deep, mocking laughter. Then... a voice speaks.
>"Open your eyes, coward. I'm not here for your money."
>The mysterious voice is obviously female, and is a threatening contralto. You gently open your eyes...
>And are shocked to be face to face with... her.
>The beast from your story. Her unkempt grey fur, blood red eyes, and vicious claws confirm that much. She gives you a sinister, fanged grin, revealing far too many teeth to count.
>"Well? I assume you were about to post that little story, weren't you? What do you say I give it a little proofreading first, eh?"
>Her tone, and the pressure of her clawed hands on your shoulders, tells you that you have no choice.

>Chapter 6, Mom, Look, An Alien!

>It’s the 22nd now, a full week since the night in the woods.
>And a full week since you or anyone has seen or heard anything from Kim.
>How much of that time you spent aboard the Triangle is difficult to say. Your best guesses suggest around twenty hours, assuming nothing fucky went on chronologically, and no time elapsed between the right seat and your chair in the basement.
>Given the latter is a consideration at all, you don’t have very high hopes for the former.
>Regardless, you’ve been back home five largely sleepless nights.
>Your car is here, but there’s no trace of Kim.
>No one else seems to know either, though you haven’t done much asking around.
>Nobody knows he rode with you that night. You might be worried, but you’re in no hurry to be some investigator’s number one person of interest either. Fortunately Kim’s parents are as absentee as they were wealthy.
>And besides, Kali said to keep quiet.

>She’d saved you from a collapsed lung, and mended a broken bone or two in the space of an afternoon.
>And you’d gotten to thinking she could probably kill you just as easily.
>Whom or whatever she was, she probably wasn’t someone to be trifled with.
>So you’d done like she’d said.
>You’d checked the news, scanned the radio bands, and monitored 7000-7300 khz every hour on the hour.

>>13884340
The literal character translation is

You[SPC]were[SPC]followed.[SPC][INVALID]
They have Kim.[SPC][INVALID][INVALID]
Run.

[INVALID] is the sequence 0001010
This is the 7bit ascii for LF, or line feed, which means go to a new line. Since it's saying go to a new line, those spaces at the end of each line are pointless. I guess you only really wanted spaces, and forgot to remove the newlines from your batches.

That aside, the LF characters it gave you are invalid, and should really be 00001010 to match the rest of it being 8bit. ASCII was originally a seven bit encoding, and to make it line up nicely with eight bit systems they just stuck a zero at the front of all the characters. There are actually really convenient quirks intended to make the binary easy to read for a human: the last four bits tell you the letter, while the third bit determines if it's upper or lower case, for instance. There's similar quirks making numbers easy to identify, or relating to the effect of the shift key on the 1960's version of a QWERTY layout (which is what's going on with the third bit and changing case, and also controls a lot of how symbol characters behave)

Binary data is just 0's or 1's, on or off. Pretty much all computers operate on bytes, collections of 8 bits. All the data in a computer is just a long string of bytes. The structure is just an agreed upon standard for how to interpret it. You could open an image file as a plain text document or vice versa, it won't make sense, but it's just 1's and 0's all the same. Like, the single byte 01010001 could be a number, character, greyscale intensity, etc. It all depends on how you want to interpret it. File extensions exist to make it more obvious.

>>13884340
Its actually more convenient to do it in hexadecimal since both binary and hexadecimal are counted within the framework of the decimal system.

let me count to 10 in binary:
0000 - 0
0001 - 1
0010 - 2
0011 - 3
0100 - 4
0101 - 5
0110 - 6
0111 - 7
1000 - 8
1001 - 9
1010 - 10

Now each character in hexadecimal [0-9, A-F(10-15)] can be considered the sum of every 4-bit nibble.

so if i translate the following sequence to hex:

0100 0111 1001 1011 0111 1011 1010 1100 1101 0000 1111 1011 1110 1100
4 7 9 B 7 B A C D 0 F B E C

Note how each byte counting from right to left can represent 2^(position-1) in decimal value. so from right to left with 4 bits it would be 1, 2, 4, 8 for example. Thus the total that can be represented with 4 bits (1 nibble) is 1 + 2 + 4 + 8 = 15 excluding the special case 0000, so a total of 16 if that case is included.

Now all values are represented in binary, whether it is printed as a character, or as a number, depends on an external instruction of inary provided to the computer. We have standards to decide between these, for instance the 127-Character ASCII standard. In essence, each letter is represented by a decimal value (@ for example is 64) which is represented by binary. So @ would be 0100 0000 which is equivalent to 64 in decimal, or 40 in hexadecimal.

Just look up ASCII tables and you should be good senpai. Wikipedia is your friend. I know there is a way to manually compile a .txt file into byte-code that can be directly executed on your system, but i don't know how.

Got anymore questions feel free to ask, i'm studying this stuff and teaching is the best way to learn.

It has startlingly good characterization for a superhero story, a really unique and detailed system for how powers work, and despite being long it doesn’t bog down.

But the thing people love the most about Parahumans is how creative it is, both in what powers everyone has and how they use them. The protagonist starts out being able to control insects like a Starcraft player and beats down a guy who gradually turns into a dragon. One of her allies has an automatic bat-deduction ability that makes super educated guesses about anything she concentrates on, but that she can never turn off - which makes it impossible for her to have sex with anyone because of how many turn-offs it supplies. One of their early enemies is an Iron Man type who can build anything he can imagine... but only once. Trying to repeat himself causes his inventions to malfunction. He has no idea that’s the case and can’t understand why his stuff keeps breaking. Etc. etc.

Don’t actually read it before writing that story, because it’s really fucking long. But there are a lot of cool ideas for how to approach superpowers in it.
